  "Idea": "Entity linking systems frequently struggle with NIL prediction because they are trained predominantly on positive (linkable) examples, leading to overconfidence in assigning mentions to known entities even when no valid link exists. Current approaches either treat NIL as a default class or use fixed thresholds on similarity scores, both of which fail under distributional shifts or ambiguous contexts. To address this, we propose 'Learning Plausibility-Aware Representations via Asymmetric Prototypical Networks for Robust NIL Prediction'—a framework that redefines NIL detection as a problem of plausibility estimation rather than binary classification. Our method leverages prototypical networks but introduces asymmetry in the similarity computation: for each input mention-context pair, we compute its similarity to a set of learned prototypes representing known entity types and domains. However, instead of using symmetric distance metrics, we train a direction-sensitive comparator that assesses whether the input is *sufficiently close* to any prototype (supporting a non-NIL prediction) or *significantly divergent* in key semantic dimensions (supporting a NIL prediction). Crucially, the model learns a dynamic plausibility threshold per prototype cluster using meta-learning on episodes sampled from low-density regions of the embedding space, simulating ambiguous or unseen entity scenarios. This allows the system to adaptively determine when a mention falls outside the scope of plausible linkage. Additionally, we introduce a regularization mechanism during training that penalizes high-confidence assignments to known entities when contextual cues suggest ambiguity (e.g., rare names, cross-domain references), thereby reducing overfitting to frequent non-NIL cases. The architecture outputs both a link prediction and a plausibility score with diagnostic explanations derived from the most dissimilar prototype dimensions, enabling interpretability. We evaluate our mode